# Coding Structure and Testing Principles

## Architecture

- Follow SOLID principles for all new implementation and refactoring.
- Keep business logic separated from UI/framework-specific concerns.
- Prefer dependency injection and dependency inversion for collaborators.
- If a module is hard to test, refactor architecture first instead of skipping tests.
- To achieve SOLID in practice, use suitable design patterns when helpful, for example:
  - Strategy
  - Factory Method / Abstract Factory
  - Adapter
  - Facade
  - Decorator
  - Observer (Publisher-Subscriber)
  - Command (or UseCase style)
  - Repository

## Unit Test Requirements

- Any new business logic must include unit tests.
- Unit tests should cover:
  - normal/success path
  - error/failure path
  - key edge cases
- Bug fixes in business logic must include a regression unit test.
- Avoid hidden hard dependencies in business logic (static/singleton direct usage) that block unit testing.

## Delivery Standard

- Prioritize testable design over quick but tightly coupled implementation.
- New behavior is considered incomplete if business logic tests are missing without technical justification.
